Implement reading and writing the two manifest files: chipper-slugs and chipper-queue.

chipper-slugs maps ticket filenames to unique slugs:
  filename = slug

chipper-queue uses slug as the key and writes entries in three sections:
  slug = status [index]   <- top: active + prioritized, sorted by index
  slug = status           <- middle: active, unsorted (no index)
                          <- blank line separator
  slug = status           <- bottom: completed (done/cancelled/archived), appended over time

Completed tickets always lose their index when written. The three-section
structure means the file is a living record: work rises to the top, completed
work accumulates at the bottom.

Requirements:
- Parse and write both files in key = value plaintext format
- Detect unregistered files (in tickets dir but not in chipper-slugs)
- Detect unsorted tickets (in chipper-slugs but not in chipper-queue)
- Detect orphaned entries (in chipper-slugs or chipper-queue but file does not exist on disk)
- Enforce slug uniqueness on write
- Handle sparse index gaps (default 1000); on conflict, bump only the affected entries
- Expose a clean internal API for all other commands to use
